\end_inset

.
 When they are not linked, Superbot modules may communicate via IR transmitters
 and receivers on their docking surfaces, which allow them to execute autonomous
 docking maneuvers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Capabilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Superbots may assume a wide range of locomotive configurations, as shown
 in Figure 2.
 A single Superbot may use its end effectors to move in a “caterpillar”
 gait, and a single chain of Superbots may use a wave-like motion to move
 sideways in a snake-like “sidewinder” fashion.
 Branched chains of Superbots may exhibit many different types of walking
 gaits, including bipedal, quadrupedal, and hexapedal motion.
 In addition to locomotion, collections of Superbots are capable of other
 complex activities, such as digging in soil and object manipulation 
